{{refimprove|date=December 2007}}

[[astronomy|Astronomers]] use the term '''intrinsic brightness''' to refer to how bright a star would be without the effects of distance or absorption due to interstellar dust or gas. While a bright distant star's [[apparent magnitude|apparent brightness]] might be less than a nearby dim star, due to the [[inverse square law]] for brightness, astronomers can discuss its intrinsic brightness meaning how bright the stars would be at a common distance. A star's intrinsic brightness is measured by its [[absolute magnitude]].

